<section class="border-y border-border/50 bg-muted/30 py-12 lg:py-16">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-foreground sm:text-2xl">
      The problem with prompt evaluation
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-6 max-w-[65ch] space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      <p>
        When you know which prompt version produced an output, <span class="redacted">you're biased</span>.
        You favor the version you wrote, the newer one, the one from the fancier
        model. Every evaluation becomes a confirmation of what you already believe.
      </p>
      <p>
        Clinical trials solved this decades ago with <span class="redacted redacted-delay">blinding</span>.
        Researchers don't know which patients received the drug and which got the
        placebo — and the results are better for it.
      </p>
      <p class="font-medium text-foreground">
        Blind Bench brings that same rigor to prompt engineering.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

